<h3>Main directions of studies</h3>
<br>
<ul>


<li>Theoretical studies of the electronic and magnetic structure of solids.</li>

<li>Calculations of equations of states and fundamental thermodynamical properties of solids.</li>

<li>Analysis of hybridisation effects of electronic states and their relation 
with stability of investigated systems, elastic and magnetic properties.</li>

<li>Investigation of spin polarization effects in the electronic structure of  d- and f-metal compounds.</li>


</ul>
<br>
<br>



<h3>Main results</h3>
<br>
<ul>


<li>For the first time anisotropic magnetic susceptibility of  metalic systems with 
hexagonal and tetragonal structure was calculated <i>ab initio</i>.</li>

<li>Theoretically studied the electronic structure and magnetic properties of compounds 
based on Mn, Fe and Co oxides.</li>

<li>Theoretically investigated magnetic properties of new iron-based HTSC FeSe(Te).</li>

<li>The nature of magneto-volume effects in a number of compounds of transition, 
rare-earth metals and actinides was studied.</li>

<li>Detailed calculations of the electronic structure, elastic and magnetic properties of diborides, 
hexaborides and dodecaborides of transition and rare-earth metals have been performed.</li>


</ul>
<br>
<br>



<h3>Theoretical methods</h3>
<br>
<ul>


<li>We use modern, complementary methods of computational solid state physics for 
self-consistent calculations of the solids band structure within the density functional theory (DFT): 
full-potential methods of linear muffin-tin orbital (FP-LMTO) and 
linearised augmented plane wave (FP-LAPW, the ELK implementation), and 
pseudopotential method (Quantum Espresso implementation).</li>

<li>The FP-LMTO method is modified to perform self-consistent calculations of the 
spin-polarized electronic structure in the presence of an external magnetic field.</li>

<li>The calculations are carried out using the grid-cluster of the ILTPE of NAS of Ukraine.</li>


</ul>

